<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">40118073</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>22</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>22</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Electronic-Print"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1555-0273</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>20</Volume><Issue>6</Issue><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Jun</Month><Day>01</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>International journal of sports physiology and performance</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Int J Sports Physiol Perform</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Gastrointestinal Temperature Measurement From Ingestible Pills Provided 3&#xa0;Hours Preexercise Is Insufficient to Avoid Interference Caused by Tepid Water Ingestion.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>856</StartPage><EndPage>859</EndPage><MedlinePgn>856-859</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1123/ijspp.2024-0440</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="PURPOSE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">This study aimed to evaluate the effect of telemetric-pill ingestion timing on gastrointestinal temperature measurements during exercise with tepid fluid intake.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">Twelve participants swallowed temperature pills 12, 3, or 0.5&#xa0;hours before completing 60&#xa0;minutes of treadmill running, consuming 200&#xa0;mL of room-temperature water every 15&#xa0;minutes.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Pills ingested 0.5 or 3&#xa0;hours before exercise resulted in significantly lower gastrointestinal temperature compared with those ingested 12&#xa0;hours prior.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">These results indicate that ingesting pills closer to exercise with fluid ingestion may confound gastrointestinal temperature measurements, underlining the need for sufficient ingestion time before exercise to avoid interference with fluid intake.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Mougin</LastName><ForeName>Lo&#xef;s</ForeName><Initials>L</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0009-0002-9401-6080</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Sport, Exercise and Health Sciences, National Centre for Sport and Exercise Medicine, Loughborough University, Loughborough, United Kingdom.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Cable</LastName><ForeName>Thomas G</ForeName><Initials>TG</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0009-0002-6194-5924</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Sport, Exercise and Health Sciences, National Centre for Sport and Exercise Medicine, Loughborough University, Loughborough, United Kingdom.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Mears</LastName><ForeName>Stephen A</ForeName><Initials>SA</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0003-3941-9426</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Sport, Exercise and Health Sciences, National Centre for Sport and Exercise Medicine, Loughborough University, Loughborough, United Kingdom.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>James</LastName><ForeName>Lewis J</ForeName><Initials>LJ</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0001-6514-5823</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Sport, Exercise and Health Sciences, National Centre for Sport and Exercise Medicine, Loughborough University, Loughborough, United Kingdom.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2025</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>21</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>United States</Country><MedlineTA>Int J Sports Physiol Perform</MedlineTA><